Short answer: we can't cause it's really expensive.

Long answer: it currently costs around $10,000 per kilogram to get something into orbit. As we have collected millions of kilos of waste over the years, it isn't realistic in any monetary world. The bigger issue, the amount of energy it would take to accomplish this task outside of a monetary world would be beyond the upper limits of our possible energy output. Moreover, we won't have enough energy until we achieve the limits of a 1st level civilization. Currently we haven't even reached that level. We are still are level 0 civilization.

Seems like this is making a couple bad assumptions. Like, they're comparing it to launching manned rockets and scientific probes. Really important stuff that requires a lot of effort to not only get it where it's going but make sure the contents don't die/break. This is trash. We wouldn't about damage to the contents beyond making sure the container doesn't break open and spill the trash into Earth orbit. So am I missing something, or wouldn't this look less like a space shuttle launch and more like building a really big cannon to shoot stuff in space towards the general direction of away?

That still might not be practical, but not sure how much the cost of existing methods and infrastructure are applicable here.

Didn't know all that stuff about orbital mechanics making it harder to fire something at the sun. But that just means you'd want to substitute Jupiter.

snippet.textDisplay: Currently, it's a matter of cost. It costs too dang much to shoot trash into space. It's way cheaper to buy some land and dump it and cover it. If, at some point in the probably very distant future, land becomes so costly and transports to space become cheap enough, we will probably start shooting out trash into space. I don't see this happening in our lifetimes, but trash is a big problem. The day will come when we have nowhere else to put our trash and incinerating it is not sustainable. Eventually, we will either need to recycle ALL of it, or find a cheap enough way to get it off the planet, or, if it gets too bad, get ourselves off the planet.
